Sequencing result showed correct sequences from 1479bp to 1986bp

Based on the Stem Loop (5?-GAT ATC CCG TGG AGG GGC GCG TGG TGG CGG CTG CAG CCG CCA CCA CGC GCC CCT CCA CGG GAT ATC-3?) by Doma and Parker, Nature. 2006 Mar 23;440(7083):561-4 at the same location of the 5? UTR of PGK1 gene as Aditya Radhakrishnan et al. Cell. 2016 Sep 22;167(1):122-132.e9., point mutate to gradually remove the Stem Loop.
According to D. MUHLRAD et al. MOLECULAR AND CELLULAR BIOLOGY, Apr. 1995, p. 2145–2156, they inserted the stem loop in upstream of start codon. Original stem loop has 8 codon pair stems. To shorten the length of stem, I point mutate T->A and G->C in one side of stem.

sequence: pHPHS524_pU6_sgRNAdropout_bGHpA_attB_Cas9-NLS-T2A-mCherry-T2A-Puro_SV40pA_KanR. Sequencing results: Dirty sequence data but based on the traces we can confirm 417P2 got in but no 417P3. It seemed to lose T7_promomoter-bGH_PA_terminator-attB-3xFLAG-SV40 NLS-Cas9-nucleoplasmin NLS-T2A-mCherry-T2A-Pure and it is connected to SV40-PA with a ~100bp nonspecific junction. This seems to have no attB sites and puro, so it will not affect transfection. Based on 30-40% contamination of this small unwanted plasmid in pHPHS524 we estimated the actual pHPHS524 has 180000-210000 colony variation. This is close to our bottleneck so we can directly use this plasmids.

This high parent contamination is from that the parent plasmid (pHPHS528) includes the grandparent plasmid (pHPHS525) contamination because AscI cutting was not that good. For future use, we need to gel purify pHPHS528 to remove the grandparent contamination (pHPHS525). Then we can make better next step plasmids. Also we may want to use NotI or other cutitng site instead of AscI which has this uncut issue.
We decided to move forward by using pHPHS530.
